A `StakeCredential` in Aiken represents the delegation and rewards withdrawal conditions for a stake address. You work with it by pattern matching on its `Referenced` wrapper to handle both inline and pointer-based credentials.

Example usage:

```aiken
use cardano/address.{StakeCredential, Inline, ByReference}

fn verify_stake(stake_cred: StakeCredential) -> Bool {
  when stake_cred is {
    Inline(credential) -> {
      // Handle inline credential
      validate_credential(credential)
    }
    ByReference(pointer) -> {
      // Handle pointer-based credential (CIP-0019)
      validate_pointer(pointer)
    }
  }
}
```

The `Inline` variant means the `Credential` is embedded directly in the output. The `ByReference` variant uses a pointer (slot, transaction index, output index) to reference the credential on-chain, which saves space and allows shared credential references across multiple outputs.

`StakeCredential` en Aiken encapsula la credencial de stake usando el tipo `Referenced<Credential>`, que puede ser inline o por referencia.

Ejemplo práctico:

```aiken
use cardano/address.{StakeCredential, Inline, ByReference}

validator stake_validator(stake_cred: StakeCredential) {
  fn check_stake_delegation(redeemer: Data) -> Bool {
    when stake_cred is {
      Inline(cred) -> {
        // Credencial embebida directamente
        cred == expected_credential()
      }
      ByReference(ptr) -> {
        // Credencial por referencia (CIP-0019)
        verify_pointer_matches(ptr)
      }
    }
  }
}
```

La ventaja de usar `ByReference` es que reduce el tamaño de la transacción cuando múltiples outputs comparten la misma credencial de stake. El puntero (pointer) especifica la ubicación on-chain del dato que contiene la credencial real.

Usa `Inline` cuando la credencial es única o necesitas que esté explícita en el output. Usa `ByReference` cuando optimizas transacciones o compartes credenciales entre múltiples salidas.

