use aiken/collection/list
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

validator enriched_signatories {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let sentinel: VerificationKeyHash = #"deadbeef"
    let enriched = list.push(self.extra_signatories, sentinel)
    !list.is_empty(enriched)
  }
}
```

Puedes combinar `list.foldl` con `list.push` para invertir una lista: en cada paso, el elemento actual se empuja al frente del acumulador, resultando en un orden inverso.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list

let original = [1, 2, 3, 4]

let reversed =
  list.foldl(
    original,
    [],
    fn(elem, acc) { list.push(acc, elem) },
  )

// reversed == [4, 3, 2, 1]
```

Esto funciona porque `foldl` procesa elementos de izquierda a derecha y `push` siempre coloca el elemento al frente del acumulador, invirtiendo el orden original.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list

let step1 = list.push([2, 3], 1)
let step2 = list.push(step1, 0)
// step2 == [0, 1, 2, 3]
```

Both the spread syntax and `list.push` produce identical results. The refactored version is preferable when building lists inside functional pipelines or when you want to keep a consistent style throughout the codebase.

```aiken
