    let quantities: List<Int> =
      minted_tokens
        |> assets.tokens(self.mint, policy_id)
        |> fn(_dict) {
             // Flatten to (AssetName, Int) pairs and check quantities
             assets.flatten(self.mint)
           }
        // Use flatten on self.mint to get (PolicyId, AssetName, Int) triples
    list.all(
      assets.flatten(self.mint)
        |> list.filter(fn(triple) {
             let (pid, _name, _qty) = triple
             pid == policy_id
           }),
      fn(triple) {
        let (_pid, _name, qty) = triple
        qty == 1
      },
    )
  }
}
```

Este validador obtiene todos los activos acuñados bajo la `policy_id` actual usando `assets.flatten(self.mint)`, filtra por la política correcta y luego usa `list.all` para asegurar que todas las cantidades sean exactamente `1`.

## Security Implication of `list.all` on Empty Lists

`list.all` uses **vacuous truth**: it returns `True` when the list is empty because no element can violate the predicate.

### Potential Vulnerability

Consider a validator that checks all extra signatories are authorised:

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

// VULNERABLE: passes even with zero signatories
validator naive_auth {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    list.all(
      self.extra_signatories,
      fn(signer: VerificationKeyHash) { signer == #"deadbeef" },
    )
  }
}
```

If an attacker submits a transaction with **no** `extra_signatories`, `list.all` returns `True` and the validator passes — even though no one actually signed!

### Fix: Require at Least One Signatory

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

const owner: VerificationKeyHash = #"deadbeef"

validator safe_auth {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let signatories = self.extra_signatories
    // Guard: list must not be empty
    !list.is_empty(signatories) && list.all(
      signatories,
      fn(signer: VerificationKeyHash) { signer == owner },
    )
  }
}
```

**Rule of thumb**: Whenever `list.all` guards access control, always pair it with a non-emptiness check (`!list.is_empty(...)` or `list.any(...)`) to prevent bypass via empty lists.

