Puedes usar `interval.contains/2` para verificar si un punto entero está dentro de un `Interval`. El rango de validez de una transacción (`self.validity_range`) es de tipo `ValidityRange = Interval`, por lo que se puede usar directamente.

```aiken
use aiken/interval
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction}

validator check_slot {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let target_slot = 1000
    interval.contains(self.validity_range, target_slot)
  }
}
```

`interval.contains/2` evalúa si `target_slot` cae dentro del intervalo, teniendo en cuenta si cada `IntervalBound` es inclusivo o exclusivo. Por ejemplo:
- Si el rango es `[900, 1100]` (ambos `IntervalBound` inclusivos), `contains(rango, 1000)` devuelve `True`.
- Si el rango es `(1000, 1100]` (límite inferior exclusivo), `contains(rango, 1000)` devuelve `False`.

Both `interval.hull/2` and `interval.intersection/2` operate on `Interval` values and produce a new `Interval` by combining the `IntervalBound` values of the two inputs:

- **`interval.hull(iv1, iv2)`**: returns the smallest interval that contains both `iv1` and `iv2`. It selects the *minimum* lower `IntervalBound` and the *maximum* upper `IntervalBound` from the two intervals.
- **`interval.intersection(iv1, iv2)`**: returns the overlap between `iv1` and `iv2`. It selects the *maximum* lower `IntervalBound` and the *minimum* upper `IntervalBound`.

The inclusivity of the resulting `IntervalBound` values is computed correctly in each case.

```aiken
use aiken/interval

// [10, 30] hull [20, 50] => [10, 50]
let a = interval.between(10, 30)
let b = interval.between(20, 50)
let combined = interval.hull(a, b)
// interval.contains(combined, 5)  // False
// interval.contains(combined, 10) // True
// interval.contains(combined, 50) // True

// [10, 30] intersection [20, 50] => [20, 30]
let overlap = interval.intersection(a, b)
// interval.contains(overlap, 15) // False
// interval.contains(overlap, 25) // True
// interval.contains(overlap, 35) // False
```

In a validator context, you might use `intersection` to find the overlap between the transaction's validity range and an allowed window, then check that it is non-empty with `interval.is_empty`.

`IntervalBoundType` is a type defined in `aiken/interval` that describes the kind of bound used in an `IntervalBound`. It has three variants:

- `NegativeInfinity` — represents an unbounded lower end (negative infinity).
- `PositiveInfinity` — represents an unbounded upper end (positive infinity).
- `Finite(Int)` — represents a concrete, finite bound. The `Int` value typically represents a number of seconds or milliseconds (e.g. a POSIX timestamp used in a transaction validity range).

Example pattern matching usage:

```aiken
use aiken/interval.{IntervalBoundType}

fn describe_bound(b: IntervalBoundType) -> String {
  when b is {
    NegativeInfinity -> @"negative infinity"
    PositiveInfinity -> @"positive infinity"
    Finite(_t) -> @"finite bound"
  }
}
```

In Aiken v3 you can access `self.validity_range` (which is an `Interval`) and inspect its `lower_bound.bound_type` field, which is an `IntervalBoundType`. Here is a complete example:

```aiken
use aiken/interval.{IntervalBoundType, Finite, NegativeInfinity, PositiveInfinity}
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction}

validator my_validator {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Data>,
    _redeemer: Data,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let lower = self.validity_range.lower_bound.bound_type
    when lower is {
      Finite(_t) -> True
      NegativeInfinity -> False
      PositiveInfinity -> False
    }
  }
}
```

The `Finite(t)` variant carries the concrete timestamp (in milliseconds) as an `Int`.

```aiken
use aiken/interval.{IntervalBoundType, Finite, NegativeInfinity, PositiveInfinity}

fn bound_or_default(b: IntervalBoundType, default: Int) -> Int {
  when b is {
    Finite(t) -> t
    NegativeInfinity -> default
    PositiveInfinity -> default
  }
}
```

This function pattern-matches on the three constructors of `IntervalBoundType`. `Finite(t)` carries the concrete `Int` value (typically a POSIX timestamp in milliseconds), while `NegativeInfinity` and `PositiveInfinity` fall back to the supplied `default`.

El constructor `Finite(Int)` del tipo `IntervalBoundType` (del módulo `aiken/interval`) representa un límite concreto y finito dentro de un intervalo. El valor `Int` que lleva típicamente representa una cantidad de segundos o milisegundos, siendo muy común que almacene un timestamp POSIX cuando se usa en el rango de validez de una transacción (`validity_range`).

Se usa en contraste con los otros dos constructores del tipo:
- `NegativeInfinity` — límite inferior sin restricción.
- `PositiveInfinity` — límite superior sin restricción.

Ejemplo:
```aiken
use aiken/interval.{IntervalBoundType, Finite}

fn es_finito(b: IntervalBoundType) -> Bool {
  when b is {
    Finite(_) -> True
    _ -> False
  }
}
```

```aiken
use aiken/interval.{Finite, NegativeInfinity, PositiveInfinity}
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction}

validator deadline_validator {
  spend(
    datum: Option<Int>,
    _redeemer: Data,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    when datum is {
      None -> False
      Some(deadline) -> {
        let upper = self.validity_range.upper_bound.bound_type
        when upper is {
          Finite(t) -> t < deadline
          NegativeInfinity -> False
          PositiveInfinity -> False
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Este validador accede a `self.validity_range.upper_bound.bound_type` (un `IntervalBoundType`) y verifica que sea `Finite(t)` con `t` estrictamente menor que la fecha límite del datum.

`IntervalBoundType` (módulo `aiken/interval`) es un tipo enumerado con tres constructores que describen la naturaleza del límite de un intervalo:

| Constructor | Significado |
|---|---|
| `NegativeInfinity` | El límite no tiene cota inferior; el intervalo se extiende indefinidamente hacia el pasado. |
| `PositiveInfinity` | El límite no tiene cota superior; el intervalo se extiende indefinidamente hacia el futuro. |
| `Finite(Int)` | El límite es un valor concreto (típicamente un timestamp en segundos o milisegundos). |

**Por qué importa en validadores de tiempo:**

En Cardano, `self.validity_range` es un `Interval<Int>` cuyo límite inferior y superior son `IntervalBound` con un campo `bound_type: IntervalBoundType`. Si un validador necesita asegurarse de que una transacción sólo es válida *antes de* o *después de* cierto momento, debe comprobar que el límite relevante sea `Finite` para poder comparar el timestamp. Si fuera `PositiveInfinity` o `NegativeInfinity`, la comparación numérica no tendría sentido y el validador podría comportarse de forma insegura.

```aiken
use aiken/interval.{Finite, NegativeInfinity, PositiveInfinity}

// Comprueba que el límite superior es finito y previo a `deadline`
fn upper_before(upper_type: IntervalBoundType, deadline: Int) -> Bool {
  when upper_type is {
    Finite(t) -> t <= deadline
    NegativeInfinity -> True
    PositiveInfinity -> False
  }
}
```

You can use `interval.after(100)` from the `aiken/interval` module. It creates an interval `[100, +∞]`, meaning slot 100 is included and all values above it are also included.

```aiken
use aiken/interval

let valid_from: interval.Interval = interval.after(100)
// Equivalent to: Interval {
//   lower_bound: IntervalBound { bound_type: Finite(100), is_inclusive: True },
//   upper_bound: IntervalBound { bound_type: PositiveInfinity, is_inclusive: True },
// }
```

The lower bound is **inclusive** (i.e., 100 is part of the interval), and the upper bound extends to positive infinity (also inclusive by convention).

```aiken
use aiken/interval
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

validator time_lock {
  spend(
    datum: Option<Int>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    when datum is {
      None -> False
      Some(deadline) -> {
        let valid_range = interval.after(deadline)
        interval.includes(valid_range, self.validity_range)
      }
    }
  }
}
```

`interval.after(deadline)` constructs `[deadline, +∞]`. Then `interval.includes(valid_range, self.validity_range)` checks that the transaction's validity range is fully contained within the allowed range — meaning the tx cannot be submitted before the deadline.

```aiken
use aiken/interval
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

const start_slot: Int = 5000

validator timed_mint {
  mint(_redeemer: Void, _policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    let allowed_range = interval.after(start_slot)
    interval.includes(allowed_range, self.validity_range)
  }
}
```

`interval.after(5000)` genera el intervalo `[5000, +∞]`. Luego `interval.includes` verifica que el rango de validez de la transacción esté completamente contenido en ese intervalo, garantizando que no se pueda acuñar antes del slot 5000.

Use `interval.contains/2` to check if a specific slot is within the interval created by `interval.after`:

```aiken
use aiken/interval

let iv = interval.after(150)
// iv = [150, +∞]

let slot = 200
let is_valid: Bool = interval.contains(iv, slot)
// is_valid == True, because 200 >= 150

let too_early: Bool = interval.contains(iv, 100)
// too_early == False, because 100 < 150

let at_boundary: Bool = interval.contains(iv, 150)
// at_boundary == True, because 150 is inclusive
```

`interval.after(150)` produces `[150, +∞]` with an inclusive lower bound, so any value ≥ 150 returns `True`.

