`interval.is_entirely_before(self: Interval, point: Int) -> Bool` checks whether every point in the interval lies strictly before the given `point`. It returns `True` only if the entire interval ends before (not at) `point`.

Key behaviors based on the documentation:
```aiken
use aiken/interval

// True: interval.before(10) covers (-∞, 10], which is entirely before 15
interval.is_entirely_before(interval.before(10), 15) == True

// False: the interval includes 10, which is NOT before 10
interval.is_entirely_before(interval.before(10), 10) == False

// False: the interval includes values >= 5 (e.g., 10 > 5)
interval.is_entirely_before(interval.before(10), 5) == False

// True: interval.between(10, 20) ends at 20, which is entirely before 30
interval.is_entirely_before(interval.between(10, 20), 30) == True

// False: the interval starts at 10, which is not before 5
interval.is_entirely_before(interval.between(10, 20), 5) == False
```

Note the boundary case: `is_entirely_before(interval.before(10), 10)` returns `False` because the interval includes 10 (it is inclusive), and 10 is not *strictly before* 10.

