Si realmente necesitas lógica de comparación de `IntervalBound` personalizada, deberás implementarla tú mismo accediendo a los campos `bound_type` e `is_inclusive` del tipo `IntervalBound`.

```aiken
use aiken/interval
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

// Allowed window: slots [100, 500] inclusive
const allowed_window = interval.between(100, 500)

validator time_window_lock {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    // The validity range must be fully included within the allowed window.
    // interval.includes checks that allowed_window contains the entire validity_range.
    // Internally, the stdlib uses interval.min on upper bounds and interval.max
    // on lower bounds (via intersection) to compute the overlap.
    interval.includes(allowed_window, self.validity_range)
  }
}
```

`interval.includes(self, other)` returns `True` when `other` is a sub-interval of `self`. This relies on the same `interval.min` / `interval.max` bound-comparison semantics used in `interval.intersection`, ensuring that inclusive vs. exclusive boundaries are handled correctly at the edges of the window.

