You can use `bytearray.foldl` from `aiken/primitive/bytearray` to fold over each byte left-to-right, accumulating the integer value:

```aiken
use aiken/primitive/bytearray

// Converts a ByteArray to an integer treating it as a big-endian base-256 number
fn bytearray_to_int(bytes: ByteArray) -> Int {
  bytearray.foldl(bytes, 0, fn(byte, acc) { acc * 256 + byte })
}

// Example: bytearray_to_int(#"acab") == 44203
```

`bytearray.foldl` iterates over every byte (each in the range 0–255) from left to right, passing the current byte and the running accumulator to your callback. Starting with `0`, each step shifts the accumulator up by 256 and adds the new byte, producing a big-endian integer.

```aiken
