`assets.merge` adds the quantities of matching `(PolicyId, AssetName)` pairs together, and includes any tokens present in only one of the two values. Note that the resulting `Value` will never contain zero-quantity entries — those are automatically cleaned up.

```aiken
use cardano/assets
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction, InlineDatum}
use aiken/collection/list

pub type RewardDatum {
  reward: assets.Value
}

validator reward_top_up {
  spend(
    datum: Option<RewardDatum>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    when datum is {
      None -> False
      Some(d) -> {
        expect Some(own_input) =
          transaction.find_input(self.inputs, own_ref)
        let required_value =
          assets.merge(own_input.output.value, d.reward)
        list.any(
          self.outputs,
          fn(o) {
            assets.lovelace_of(o.value) >= assets.lovelace_of(required_value)
          },
        )
      }
    }
  }
}
```

`assets.merge` combina dos valores `Value` completos sumando las cantidades de todos los tokens en ambos:

```aiken
use cardano/assets

let v1 = assets.from_lovelace(1_000_000)
let v2 = assets.from_asset("policy123", "Token", 5)
let combinado = assets.merge(v1, v2)
```

En cambio, `assets.add` añade una cantidad específica de un solo token a un `Value` existente:

```aiken
let v3 = assets.add(v1, "policy123", "Token", 5)
```

Ambas funciones garantizan que el `Value` resultante no contenga entradas con cantidad cero. Usa `merge` cuando quieras unir dos `Value` completos; usa `add` cuando solo quieras ajustar la cantidad de un token concreto.

