The `fail` annotation tells Aiken's test runner that this test is expected to return `False` (or error). Passing an empty `outputs: []` means the indexer cannot find the required output for any script input, so `one_to_one_no_redeemer` must fail.

Using `list.foldl` processes the list left-to-right, so we track the current index manually and append rather than prepend, giving us the same ascending-index order without relying on `indexed_foldr` + `push`.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/address.{Script}
use cardano/transaction.{Input, Output}

// Replace the indexed_foldr block with:
let (_, script_input_indices, script_outputs) =
  list.foldl(
    inputs,
    (0, [], []),
    fn(input, acc) {
      let (idx, i_indices, outputs) = acc
      when input.output.address.payment_credential is {
        Script(_) ->
          (idx + 1, list.concat(i_indices, [idx]), list.concat(outputs, [input.output]))
        _ -> (idx + 1, i_indices, outputs)
      }
    },
  )

let indices =
  list.foldl(
    script_input_indices,
    (0, []),
    fn(script_input_index, acc) {
      let (i, pairs) = acc
      (i + 1, list.concat(pairs, [Pair(script_input_index, i)]))
    },
  ).2nd
```

> **Note:** The original `indexed_foldr` + `list.push` approach is more idiomatic and efficient in Aiken because prepending (`push`) is O(1) while `list.concat` to append is O(n). The `foldl` version above is semantically equivalent but less performant. Prefer `indexed_foldr` + `push` in production code.

