## Common Security Pitfall: Not Constraining Other Asset Names Under the Same Policy

A frequent mistake is only checking the quantity of a specific asset name without verifying that **no other asset names** are minted under the same policy. This allows an attacker to mint arbitrary tokens under the same policy in the same transaction.

### Vulnerable pattern
```aiken
// DANGEROUS: only checks one asset name
validator nft_policy(asset_name: ByteArray) {
  mint(_redeemer: Void, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    assets.quantity_of(self.mint, policy_id, asset_name) == 1
  }
}
```
An attacker can also mint `other_asset` under `policy_id` in the same transaction, and this validator will still pass.

### Safe pattern — constrain the entire policy
```aiken
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}
use aiken/collection/list

validator nft_policy(asset_name: ByteArray) {
  mint(_redeemer: Void, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    let policy_tokens = assets.tokens(self.mint, policy_id)
    // Flatten to a list of (AssetName, Int) pairs and verify exactly one entry
    let flat = assets.flatten(assets.restricted_to(self.mint, [policy_id]))
    list.length(flat) == 1 && assets.quantity_of(self.mint, policy_id, asset_name) == 1
  }
}
```

**Key takeaways:**
- Always verify **both** that the correct asset name has the expected quantity **and** that no other tokens are minted under your policy.
- Use `assets.tokens(self.mint, policy_id)` to inspect all asset names under the policy, or `assets.restricted_to` + `assets.flatten` to enumerate and count them.
- This is a standard defense-in-depth pattern in Cardano smart contract design.

You can extract the list of asset names minted under your policy, then compare its length to the deduplicated version using `list.unique`. If both lengths are equal, all asset names are unique.

```aiken
use cardano/assets
use aiken/collection/list

validator my_policy {
  mint(redeemer: Void, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    let minted_names =
      self.mint
        |> assets.tokens(policy_id)
        |> assets.flatten
        |> list.map(fn(triple) { let (_, name, _) = triple; name })

    list.length(minted_names) == list.length(list.unique(minted_names))
  }
}
```

`list.unique` removes duplicate elements, so if the original and deduplicated lists have the same length, no duplicates exist.

```aiken
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}
use aiken/collection/list

validator single_asset_policy {
  mint(redeemer: Void, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    let minted_tokens =
      self.mint
        |> assets.tokens(policy_id)

    let asset_names =
      minted_tokens
        |> assets.flatten
        |> list.map(fn(triple) { let (_, name, _) = triple; name })
        |> list.unique

    list.length(asset_names) == 1
  }
}
```

This extracts all asset names minted under `policy_id`, deduplicates them with `list.unique`, and asserts there is exactly one unique name.

Enforcing uniqueness of outputs means ensuring no two outputs in a transaction are identical (e.g., same address and value). The key tool is `list.unique` from `aiken/collection/list`, which removes duplicates from a list. If the deduplicated list is the same length as the original, all elements are unique.

```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, Output}
use aiken/collection/list

fn all_outputs_unique(outputs: List<Output>) -> Bool {
  list.length(outputs) == list.length(list.unique(outputs))
}

validator unique_outputs_check {
  spend(
    datum: Option<Void>,
    redeemer: Void,
    own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    all_outputs_unique(self.outputs)
  }
}
```

The pattern is general: collect the list of items you want to be unique, apply `list.unique`, and check that the length is unchanged.

Puedes extraer todas las políticas de los valores de los inputs y luego usar `list.unique` para deduplicarlas. Si la longitud es igual, todas las políticas son únicas.

```aiken
use cardano/assets
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, Input}
use aiken/collection/list

fn unique_input_policies(inputs: List<Input>) -> Bool {
  let all_policies =
    inputs
      |> list.flat_map(
          fn(input) { assets.policies(input.output.value) },
        )

  list.length(all_policies) == list.length(list.unique(all_policies))
}

validator check_unique_policies {
  spend(
    datum: Option<Void>,
    redeemer: Void,
    own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    unique_input_policies(self.inputs)
  }
}
```

`list.flat_map` aplana las listas de políticas de cada input en una sola lista, y `list.unique` elimina los duplicados para la comparación.

```aiken
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}
use aiken/collection/list

validator no_duplicate_asset_names {
  mint(redeemer: Void, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    let names =
      self.mint
        |> assets.tokens(policy_id)
        |> assets.flatten
        |> list.map(fn(triple) { let (_, name, _) = triple; name })

    let unique_names = list.unique(names)

    list.length(names) == list.length(unique_names)
  }
}
```

Si `list.length(names) == list.length(list.unique(names))`, significa que no hay nombres repetidos entre los tokens acuñados bajo esta política.

